1
00:02:39,159 --> 00:02:40,869
Mrs Peterson!

2
00:02:41,036 --> 00:02:43,497
Ramon, hey! How's it going?

3
00:02:43,580 --> 00:02:45,457
How you doing?

4
00:02:46,166 --> 00:02:48,085
There it is, there on the desk.

5
00:02:48,168 --> 00:02:49,878
Where's she headed?

6
00:02:49,961 --> 00:02:51,588
She's snowbound, Ramon.

7
00:02:55,509 --> 00:02:57,094
See you went with the pink.

8
00:02:57,177 --> 00:03:00,472
Yeah, yeah. It's kind of a pink day today.

9
00:03:01,264 --> 00:03:03,517
I'll have another pickup for you
on Thursday.

10
00:03:03,600 --> 00:03:06,186
- All right. See you then.
- All right. Thanks.

11
00:03:41,471 --> 00:03:43,557
Peterson! Peterson!

12
00:03:44,725 --> 00:03:45,851
Peterson.

13
00:03:49,479 --> 00:03:51,940
- Mr Cowboy, <i>da?
- Da.</i>

14
00:03:57,195 --> 00:03:58,613
Mmm, it's pretty.

15
00:04:01,742 --> 00:04:03,410
It's from my wife.

16
00:05:10,477 --> 00:05:13,897
Time rules over us
without mercy,

17
00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:17,901
not caring if we're healthy or ill,
hungry or drunk,

18
00:05:17,984 --> 00:05:21,363
Russian, American, beings from Mars.

19
00:05:21,446 --> 00:05:24,658
It's like a fire. It could either destroy us
or keep us warm.

20
00:05:24,741 --> 00:05:27,244
That's why every FedEx office
has a clock.

21
00:05:27,327 --> 00:05:30,080
Because we live or we die by the clock.

22
00:05:30,163 --> 00:05:31,915
We never turn our back on it.

23
00:05:31,998 --> 00:05:37,087
And we never, ever allow ourselves
the sin of losing track of time!

24
00:05:37,754 --> 00:05:39,923
Locally, it's 1 :56.

25
00:05:40,006 --> 00:05:43,802
That means we've got
three hours and four minutes

26
00:05:43,885 --> 00:05:45,720
before the end-of-the-day's
package sort.

27
00:05:45,804 --> 00:05:49,349
That's how long we have.
That's how much time we have

28
00:05:50,267 --> 00:05:53,103
before this pulsating, accursed,
relentless taskmaster

29
00:05:53,228 --> 00:05:55,605
tries to put us out of business.

30
00:05:56,314 --> 00:05:59,025
Hey, Nicolai. Good to see you.

31
00:05:59,109 --> 00:06:00,777
How are you, kid?

32
00:06:00,861 --> 00:06:03,196
You just delivered
your very first FedEx package.

33
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:05,365
That deserves something special,

34
00:06:05,448 --> 00:06:09,286
like a Snickers bar and a CD player.

35
00:06:09,744 --> 00:06:12,873
And something to listen to.
There. Elvis Presley.

36
00:06:12,956 --> 00:06:14,708
Fifty million fans can't be wrong.

37
00:06:14,791 --> 00:06:16,626
You all recognise this, don't you?

38
00:06:16,710 --> 00:06:19,546
I took the liberty of
sending this to myself.

39
00:06:19,629 --> 00:06:24,134
I FedEx'd it before I left Memphis.

40
00:06:24,384 --> 00:06:26,761
You're probably wondering
what could be in here.

41
00:06:26,845 --> 00:06:30,932
Is it architectural plans?
Maybe technical drawings?

42
00:06:31,141 --> 00:06:33,977
Is this the new wallpaper
for the bathroom?

43
00:06:36,021 --> 00:06:38,690
It is a clock,

44
00:06:39,232 --> 00:06:40,567
which I started at absolute zero,

45
00:06:40,650 --> 00:06:44,863
and is now at 87 hours,
22 minutes and 17 seconds.

46
00:06:46,031 --> 00:06:50,160
From Memphis, America,
to Nicolai in Russia, 87 hours.

47
00:06:50,952 --> 00:06:54,372
Eighty-seven hours
is a shameful outrage.

48
00:06:54,456 --> 00:06:56,833
This is just an egg timer!

49
00:06:57,334 --> 00:07:00,253
What if it had been something else?
Like your paycheque?

50
00:07:00,337 --> 00:07:03,340
Or fresh boysenberries?
Or adoption papers?

51
00:07:03,673 --> 00:07:05,383
Eighty-seven hours is an eternity.

52
00:07:05,467 --> 00:07:07,510
The cosmos was created in less time!

53
00:07:07,594 --> 00:07:10,430
Wars have been fought
and nations toppled in 87 hours!

54
00:07:10,513 --> 00:07:12,849
Fortunes made and squandered.

55
00:07:17,562 --> 00:07:20,357
What? What are you saying about me?

56
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:21,942
I tell them, what do they expect?

57
00:07:22,025 --> 00:07:26,279
This man, when his truck broke down,
he stole a boy's bicycle.

58
00:07:26,363 --> 00:07:29,074
I borrowed it! I borrowed a kid's bike.

59
00:07:29,157 --> 00:07:32,619
I got my packages delivered,
and that is what you have to do.

60
00:07:32,702 --> 00:07:33,954
You have to do whatever it takes,

61
00:07:34,037 --> 00:07:36,039
because in three hours and two minutes

62
00:07:36,122 --> 00:07:39,417
every one of these packages
has to be on the big truck,

63
00:07:39,501 --> 00:07:41,127
on its way to the airport.

64
00:07:42,337 --> 00:07:43,797
Fifteen minutes!

65
00:07:43,880 --> 00:07:47,050
- Crunch time! Crunch time!
- Crunch time!

66
00:07:47,217 --> 00:07:50,470
Let's go! Every package
on the airport truck.

67
00:07:50,553 --> 00:07:52,722
Go! Crunch, crunch, crunch!

68
00:07:52,806 --> 00:07:54,557
- We have a big problem.
- What?

69
00:07:54,641 --> 00:07:57,435
- The truck in Red Square is stuck.
- What?

70
00:07:57,519 --> 00:08:00,146
- It's stuck.
- Stuck how? In snow? In ice?

71
00:08:00,230 --> 00:08:03,733
The most important truck,
the Kremlin truck! Many packages.

72
00:08:13,910 --> 00:08:18,164
All right. Let's put the table right here.
We'll just do the sort.

73
00:08:18,248 --> 00:08:21,001
Ah, yeah, a clamp.
That would make us stuck.

74
00:08:21,459 --> 00:08:23,837
Let's go. Unload... Get him out of there.

75
00:08:23,920 --> 00:08:26,673
Right here. Two lines, two lines.

76
00:08:26,756 --> 00:08:29,592
One to the airport truck,
one to the Moscow truck.

77
00:08:29,676 --> 00:08:30,885
Got it?

78
00:08:31,302 --> 00:08:34,139
CDG, FE, ME, Memphis
on the airport truck.

79
00:08:34,222 --> 00:08:37,600
Everything else there. Nicolai!
Tick-tock, tick-tock. Four minutes.

80
00:08:40,478 --> 00:08:42,814
<i>Hi, this is Kelly.
If you're calling for Chuck, press one.</i>

81
00:08:42,897 --> 00:08:45,400
<i>Otherwise, leave a message. Thanks.</i>

82
00:08:46,109 --> 00:08:48,987
<i>Kelly. Are you there?
Pick up, pick up, pick up.</i>

83
00:08:49,070 --> 00:08:51,031
<i>You're not there.</i>

84
00:08:51,114 --> 00:08:55,410
<i>I'm doing the sorts in Red Square,
in the shadow of Lenin's tomb.</i>

85
00:08:55,493 --> 00:08:56,745
<i>I miss you.</i>

86
00:08:56,870 --> 00:08:58,872
I miss you, I really wanna kiss you.

87
00:08:58,955 --> 00:09:01,833
I'm picking up the sweep through Paris.

88
00:09:01,916 --> 00:09:04,461
I should be back in Memphis
in about 18 hours.

89
00:09:04,544 --> 00:09:05,837
That's the good news.

90
00:09:05,920 --> 00:09:08,673
The bad news is...
I gotta go to the dentist this week.

91
00:09:08,757 --> 00:09:10,216
I got something that's hurting.

92
00:09:10,300 --> 00:09:13,553
I'll see you soon,
and you know what that means.

93
00:09:13,636 --> 00:09:16,306
Bye-bye. Nicolai!
Tick-tock, tick-tock, tick-tock!

94
00:09:34,574 --> 00:09:37,869
I absolutely, positively have to
get to Memphis tonight.

95
00:09:37,952 --> 00:09:39,913
Can't help you. Try UPS.

96
00:09:39,996 --> 00:09:42,957
Will we be able to push it
and make the sort?

97
00:09:43,041 --> 00:09:45,085
- We'll do our best.
- "Our best"?

98
00:09:45,168 --> 00:09:49,130
Gwen, what's wrong with our doctors
that Jack is certified to fly?

99
00:09:49,672 --> 00:09:51,132
Aren't you concerned?

100
00:09:51,216 --> 00:09:53,802
Terrified, but a girl's gotta do
what a girl's gotta do.

101
00:09:53,885 --> 00:09:56,930
That's the spirit. Relentless is our goal.

102
00:09:57,013 --> 00:10:01,392
What do you expect from the guy
who stole a crippled kid's bicycle?

103
00:10:01,476 --> 00:10:04,854
I borrowed it.
But I love that the kid's now crippled.

104
00:10:05,188 --> 00:10:07,440
So you missed the last truck
by two minutes?

105
00:10:07,524 --> 00:10:10,026
Two minutes. Actually, it was less.

106
00:10:10,652 --> 00:10:13,571
The plane wasn't heavy.
You could've added some fuel

107
00:10:13,655 --> 00:10:15,824
and picked up speed.

108
00:10:15,907 --> 00:10:18,701
It's about the trucks.
Today's truck was two minutes late.

109
00:10:18,785 --> 00:10:21,746
Tomorrow's will be four minutes late,
then six, eight.

110
00:10:21,830 --> 00:10:24,499
Next thing you know, we're the US Mail.

111
00:10:24,582 --> 00:10:26,960
Well, all I'm saying is,

112
00:10:27,043 --> 00:10:28,419
if you'd gotten
all those trucks on the plane,

113
00:10:28,503 --> 00:10:31,256
those Russkies would be
walking on water now.

114
00:10:31,339 --> 00:10:35,051
Hey, don't give me that look.
It's just grape juice.

115
00:10:35,135 --> 00:10:36,427
- Right, Chuck?
- Yeah.

116
00:10:36,511 --> 00:10:39,389
Yeah. It's like
a 1992 full-bodied grape juice.

117
00:10:39,472 --> 00:10:41,766
See no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil.

118
00:10:41,850 --> 00:10:44,978
We'd offer you some,
but somebody's got to fly the plane.

119
00:10:45,061 --> 00:10:47,564
Yeah, well, I "just say no," right?

120
00:10:48,940 --> 00:10:52,735
Listen, Stan, I've been meaning
to ask you, how's Mary?

121
00:10:53,528 --> 00:10:55,864
Oh. Uh, well...

122
00:10:57,282 --> 00:10:59,742
- We really don't know anything yet.
- Mmm-hmm.

123
00:11:00,493 --> 00:11:03,788
Uh, she went to the doctor yesterday,
and, uh...

124
00:11:05,582 --> 00:11:08,751
It hasn't metastasized

125
00:11:09,252 --> 00:11:11,754
as far as they can tell right now.

126
00:11:12,589 --> 00:11:14,924
It's just kind of wait and see.

127
00:11:15,300 --> 00:11:16,759
I'm so sorry.

128
00:11:17,594 --> 00:11:20,805
Tell her I'm gonna come by
and see her on my next layover.

129
00:11:20,889 --> 00:11:24,225
I want you to know, Stan,
we are all thinking about her and you,

130
00:11:24,309 --> 00:11:27,270
- and just blessings.
- Thank you, Gwen.

131
00:11:27,353 --> 00:11:29,480
<i>Hi, this is Kelly.
If you're calling for Chuck, press one.</i>

132
00:11:29,564 --> 00:11:32,233
<i>Otherwise, leave a message.</i>

133
00:11:37,906 --> 00:11:39,115
Stan...

134
00:11:40,658 --> 00:11:42,911
Listen. I heard about this...

135
00:11:45,079 --> 00:11:48,374
I heard about this doctor
down in Emory, in Atlanta.

136
00:11:48,625 --> 00:11:52,378
He's supposed to be the best.
He worked on Frank Toretto's wife.

137
00:11:52,462 --> 00:11:56,382
Frank's a systems analyst.
He played center field for us.

138
00:11:56,466 --> 00:11:59,636
You know him. The softball tournament
last Labour Day.

139
00:11:59,719 --> 00:12:01,554
Anyway, beside the point.

140
00:12:01,638 --> 00:12:05,391
Uh, what I was thinking is,
is that I could get his number,

141
00:12:06,309 --> 00:12:08,144
the doctor, and, uh...

142
00:12:09,145 --> 00:12:11,731
You know, put you all together and...

143
00:12:13,066 --> 00:12:16,819
You know, you could get this thing fixed.
You could beat it.

144
00:12:18,780 --> 00:12:20,782
Thanks, Chuck.

145
00:12:21,115 --> 00:12:23,034
So, I'll get his number.

146
00:12:30,124 --> 00:12:33,378
- And why is that?
- When it's chemically ordered...

147
00:12:45,723 --> 00:12:49,352
- Is Kelly Frears around?
- She's copying her dissertation.

148
00:13:21,259 --> 00:13:23,511
- You're home.
- Home indeed.

149
00:13:23,594 --> 00:13:25,555
I love that you're home.

150
00:13:44,907 --> 00:13:48,578
<i>Just days before Santa departs
on his annual gift-giving venture,</i>

151
00:13:48,661 --> 00:13:51,414
<i>he's been declared physically fit to fly.</i>

152
00:13:51,581 --> 00:13:55,501
<i>Santa got checked out at the
VA Hospital in Augusta, Georgia.</i>

153
00:13:55,585 --> 00:13:58,254
<i>After doctors declared the jolly old elf
in tiptop shape,</i>

154
00:13:58,338 --> 00:14:01,924
<i>Santa took off into the wild blue yonder
for an early start.</i>

155
00:14:02,050 --> 00:14:04,594
<i>In Sarajevo,
he spent the day with children,</i>

156
00:14:04,761 --> 00:14:07,263
<i>handing out presents
and even helping them decorate</i>

157
00:14:07,347 --> 00:14:09,432
<i>the special Christmas tree.</i>

158
00:14:13,811 --> 00:14:18,024
<i>Santa and elves took over the floor
at the Hong Kong Futures Exchange.</i>

159
00:14:18,149 --> 00:14:20,360
<i>Market traders bought Santa hats...</i>

160
00:14:43,424 --> 00:14:47,637
- The turkey's a bit dry, isn't it?
- No. The turkey is perfect!

161
00:14:51,557 --> 00:14:54,769
- How many did you do last night?
- Last night? 2.9 million.

162
00:14:54,852 --> 00:14:58,815
Now, you've got to be in the market
for more of these candied yams.

163
00:15:00,149 --> 00:15:02,485
2.9 has got to be the record.

164
00:15:02,610 --> 00:15:03,986
Look at those marshmallows.

165
00:15:04,987 --> 00:15:08,324
- We thought two million was a big deal.
- The glory days.

166
00:15:08,408 --> 00:15:11,369
- What'd they do the first night?
- First night?

167
00:15:11,577 --> 00:15:13,329
- Twelve.
- Twelve thousand?

168
00:15:13,579 --> 00:15:15,957
- Hell, no. Twelve.
- That's right.

169
00:15:16,040 --> 00:15:18,251
They did the sort right there
on a card table.

170
00:15:18,334 --> 00:15:21,462
And Fred Smith
had that card table bronzed.

171
00:15:21,879 --> 00:15:24,090
I've been hearing that for five years.

172
00:15:24,173 --> 00:15:28,302
- It's in his office today.
- From that to the hub at Anchorage.

173
00:15:28,386 --> 00:15:32,473
It's a perfect marriage between
technology and systems management.

174
00:15:33,641 --> 00:15:38,020
Speaking of marriage, when are you
gonna make an honest woman of Kelly?

175
00:15:38,688 --> 00:15:41,899
- How long?
- Fourteen minutes into the meal.

176
00:15:42,024 --> 00:15:44,026
You won. I owe you five.

177
00:15:44,193 --> 00:15:46,696
- Way before the pie.
- I told him.

178
00:15:46,988 --> 00:15:49,949
Right about the time the pie came out,
the marriage...

179
00:15:50,074 --> 00:15:53,077
Kelly's still recovering after that parolee.

180
00:15:53,578 --> 00:15:55,288
He was a lawyer.

181
00:15:55,663 --> 00:15:59,333
I knew it had something to do
with swearing to tell the truth.

182
00:15:59,417 --> 00:16:02,837
Remember when he fell and broke
his shoulder at the wedding reception?

183
00:16:02,962 --> 00:16:05,715
He tripped on a kerb
holding a door open for me.

184
00:16:06,299 --> 00:16:09,594
- Aunt Kelly was married?
- It's not worth remembering.

185
00:16:09,719 --> 00:16:12,054
So since her failed marriage
to the parolee...

186
00:16:12,555 --> 00:16:13,890
Oh, my God.

187
00:16:14,015 --> 00:16:17,101
Kelly can't see being with a man
who wears a pager to bed.

188
00:16:17,226 --> 00:16:19,145
What are you gonna attach it to?

189
00:16:19,645 --> 00:16:22,106
When you wear it to bed,
I hope you got one of those things

190
00:16:22,190 --> 00:16:23,941
that goes vibrating.

191
00:16:25,359 --> 00:16:27,278
I'm not touching that.

192
00:16:27,904 --> 00:16:29,989
Oh, did you hit an olive pit?

193
00:16:30,072 --> 00:16:33,701
- I thought I took all of them out.
- No, no, it's not that.

194
00:17:00,770 --> 00:17:03,147
- Okay, I'll cancel Saturday.
- No, don't.

195
00:17:03,272 --> 00:17:05,858
If I'm not here, I'm not.
But if I am, then I am.

196
00:17:05,942 --> 00:17:08,694
It's cancelled.
But you gotta be here New Year's Eve.

197
00:17:08,778 --> 00:17:11,280
Malaysia can't be that bad.

198
00:17:11,364 --> 00:17:14,033
- When do you defend your dissertation?
- January 12.

199
00:17:14,325 --> 00:17:18,538
I'm gonna have to switch over
the South America thing.

200
00:17:18,621 --> 00:17:21,123
If I do that on the third or fourth,

201
00:17:21,207 --> 00:17:22,917
I'll have to head back out on the 13th.

202
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:24,961
So long as you're here New Year's Eve.

203
00:17:25,044 --> 00:17:27,838
I will be here New Year's Eve. I promise.

204
00:17:32,051 --> 00:17:33,052
What?

205
00:17:33,719 --> 00:17:35,972
What about our Christmas?
I got a gift for you.

206
00:17:39,600 --> 00:17:41,060
We have to do it in the car.

207
00:17:46,440 --> 00:17:49,819
I'd just like a minute over here,
all right? Thanks.

208
00:17:57,285 --> 00:18:01,080
Two minutes, okay? Two more minutes.
Thanks. Hey!

209
00:18:01,163 --> 00:18:04,250
- Merry Christmas.
- I thought you were gonna stiff me.

210
00:18:04,333 --> 00:18:05,585
What is the ribbon?

211
00:18:05,668 --> 00:18:08,796
A thousand-pound test fishing line
or something?

212
00:18:08,879 --> 00:18:11,257
- Here's your fancy thing.
- Thanks.

213
00:18:15,678 --> 00:18:17,513
I love the wrapping.

214
00:18:19,515 --> 00:18:21,475
- And I love the box.
- Good.

215
00:18:23,978 --> 00:18:24,979
Oh.

216
00:18:27,106 --> 00:18:30,568
Oh, my. Oh, that is terrific.

217
00:18:31,694 --> 00:18:33,863
My granddaddy used it
on the Southern Pacific.

218
00:18:36,699 --> 00:18:40,161
Hey, I took this.
This is my favourite picture of you.

219
00:18:42,371 --> 00:18:43,706
You know what I'm gonna do?

220
00:18:43,789 --> 00:18:46,917
I'm always gonna keep this
on Memphis time.

221
00:18:51,505 --> 00:18:52,715
Kelly time.

222
00:18:52,882 --> 00:18:53,883
Hmm.

223
00:18:54,300 --> 00:18:56,802
You haven't said anything
about your presents.

224
00:18:56,886 --> 00:19:01,223
I'm sorry. No, I love them.
Look at my journal. Ah!

225
00:19:01,307 --> 00:19:05,102
- What about the pager?
- Real leather. Gold on the pages!

226
00:19:05,311 --> 00:19:08,105
- Did you like the pager or not?
- Yes. I love it.

227
00:19:08,189 --> 00:19:11,067
Look at him
in his little blue Russian house.

228
00:19:11,233 --> 00:19:12,985
- It's from Russia.
- My God.

229
00:19:13,736 --> 00:19:15,946
- It's not one of those loud ones?
- No.

230
00:19:16,030 --> 00:19:20,242
You can program it so it vibrates
and lights up and see it in the dark.

231
00:19:20,743 --> 00:19:23,204
It seems like a real nice...pager.

232
00:19:24,580 --> 00:19:27,208
- Sorry about the towels.
- I love them!

233
00:19:27,291 --> 00:19:29,627
- You're hard to shop for.
- Every time I wash my hands,

234
00:19:29,752 --> 00:19:32,254
- I will think of you.
- All right, I gotta go.

235
00:19:33,214 --> 00:19:34,882
Merry Christmas.

236
00:19:35,466 --> 00:19:36,842
- Merry Christmas.
